Problem

Scenario

Nowadays, there has been a noticeable decline in people’s happiness levels, accompanied by a rise in mental health issues. This problem manifests in all aspects of our daily lives, such as work-related stress, social isolation, family responsibilities, and more. The decline in happiness not only affects individuals but also has repercussions for our community and society. If this trend continues to worsen, it will become a significant problem.

In recent years, we have observed a concerning trend: a decline in global happiness, which has captured our interest and motivated us to focus our research on happiness scores. According to Ipsos (2019), two-thirds of adults globally (64%) across 28 countries consider themselves happy. This prevalence of happiness is down 6 points from 70% in 2018. It is still 3 points higher than in March 2017 (61%) but 13 points below its December 2011 level of 77%.

The World Happiness Report (2024) highlights a decrease in happiness among those born after 1980. Additionally, a Gallup International survey at the end of 2021 showed a decline in global optimism and happiness compared to the previous year. This downward trend is linked to various factors, including economic instability, increasing inequality, and socio-political unrest. These findings suggest that happiness is a dynamic state, varying over time and across generations, influenced by numerous elements.

Given these considerations, we have chosen global happiness scores as the focus of our assignment and aim to identify the factors influencing these scores through regression analysis. Utilizing the 2019 happiness score data from Kaggle, we will conduct a comprehensive regression analysis to examine how various factors affect happiness.


Background

Throughout history, the pursuit of happiness has remained a central focus in human societies. In recent years, the Happiness Index Score has gained prominence as a significant measure of well-being, attracting substantial attention as an indicator of a country’s overall prosperity and quality of life. The factors influencing happiness vary widely across countries and cultures. While universally sought, happiness can be defined differently by individuals. According to Cherry (2022), happiness encompasses a range of positive emotions such as fulfillment, joy, satisfaction, and contentment. Moreover, it signifies not just fleeting positivity but a state of well-being characterized by living a meaningful and deeply satisfying life. Achieving happiness, a crucial aspect of human existence, involves striking a balance between short-term pleasures and long-term goals (The Psychology Today Editorial Team, n.d.).


Problem Statement

Given the noticeable decline in global happiness levels and the accompanying rise in mental health issues, it is crucial to identify the factors that most significantly influence happiness. This study aims to develop predictive models using various combinations of factors, including GDP per capita, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make life choices, generosity, perceptions of corruption, and a categorical variable (Region_europe, where 0 represents non-European regions and 1 represents European regions). The objective is to determine the optimal combination of factors that best predict happiness scores and to develop the most effective model for determining happiness scores based on these factors. By leveraging regression analysis on the 2019 happiness score data from Kaggle, we seek to uncover actionable insights that can inform policies and initiatives aimed at reversing the decline in happiness and improving well-being worldwide. The ultimate goal is to use the best effective model developed to guide efforts in enhancing global happiness.


Data set

Data description

The dataset used for the analysis is the 2019 Happiness Index dataset, sourced from Kaggle. It includes various variables that measure and influence happiness across different countries. The specific variables used in the analysis are:

Independent Variables

  1. GDP per capita (GDP) - Represents the economic well-being of a country’s residents.
  2. Social support (SS) - Measures the extent to which individuals have access to support from family, friends, and other social networks.
  3. Healthy life expectancy (HLE) - Indicates the length of time individuals can expect to live in good health.
  4. Freedom to make life choices (FTMLC) - Represents the level of autonomy and control individuals have over their lives.
  5. Generosity (GEN) - Reflects the quality of being kind and giving.
  6. Perception of corruption (POC) - Shows the extent to which corruption is perceived to be prevalent in a society.
  7. Region_europe (Europe): Divides the countries into two categories: European Region (1) and Non-European Region (0). Region_europe is also a categorical variable.


Dependent Variable

  • Happiness Score (Score) - A measure used in the field of happiness studies to quantify the level of happiness or well-being of individuals or groups.


Data source

The dataset is sourced from Kaggle and can be accessed using the following link: 2019 Happiness Index Dataset

Simple Linear Regression

Model 1: Score (y) against GDP per capita (x)

Summary

colnames(data_2019) <- c("Rank","CoR","Europe","Score","GDP","SS","HLE","FTMLC","Gen","POC")
SLR <- lm(Score ~ GDP, data = data_2019)
summary(SLR)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Score ~ GDP, data = data_2019)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.22044 -0.48361  0.00828  0.48433  1.47409 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   3.3993     0.1353   25.12   <2e-16 ***
## GDP           2.2181     0.1369   16.20   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.679 on 154 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6303, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6278 
## F-statistic: 262.5 on 1 and 154 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16


Least square regression line equation:

\(\hat{y}\) = 3.3993 + 2.2181\(x\)


Interpretation for estimated coefficients:

Intercept, \(\beta_0\): On average, the model predicts \(score\) to be 3.3993 when the \(GDP.per.capita\) is 0.

Slope, \(\beta_1\): On average, the model predicts \(Score\) to be increase by 2.2181, for every 1 unit increase in \(GDP.per.capita\).


Interpretation for Coefficient of determination

R-squared: 63.03% of the variation in \(Score\) can be explained by variation in \(GDP.per.capita\).


Scatterplot

data_2019 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = GDP, y = Score))+
  geom_point(size = 2,
             color = "darkorange2",
             alpha = .6)+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F)+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "Score explained by GDP.per.capita",
       x = "GDP.per.capita",
       Y = "Score")+
  theme(plot.title =
          element_text(size = 16,
                       face = "bold",

                       hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text =
          element_text(size = 10,
                       face = "bold"),
        axis.title =
          element_text(size = 13,
                       color = "steelblue",
                       face = "bold"))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The scatter plot shows a positive linear relationship between GDP per capita and the score. This means that as GDP per capita increases, the score also tends to increase.


Significant Test

Determine at 1% significance level for testing \(\beta_1\).

\(Ho:\beta_1=0\) vs \(H1:\beta_1\neq0\)

Decision rule: Reject \(H_o\) if \(p-value < \alpha\)

Decision: Since \(p-value < \alpha\), reject \(H_o\) .

Conclusion: There is a linear relationship between \(Score\) and \(GDP.per.capita\).

Using the code above we can show that this SLR model predicts the score for happiness of a country will be 6.17203, 6.904019 and 5.684038 if the GDP.per.capita is 1.25, 1.58 and 1.03 respectively.

Residual Analysis

Scatterplot
data_2019 %>%
  mutate(predicted = predict(lm(Score ~ GDP, data = data_2019))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = GDP, y = Score))+
  geom_point(size = 1.5, alpha = .5)+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F)+
  geom_segment(aes(xend = GDP, yend = predicted), color = "red")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "Score explained by GDP.per.capita",
       x = "GDP.per.capita",
       Y = "Score")+
  theme(plot.title =
          element_text(size = 16,
                       face = "bold",
                       color = "steelblue",
                       hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text =
          element_text(size = 10,
                       face = "bold"),
        axis.title =
          element_text(size = 13,
                       color = "steelblue",))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • Positive Relationship: The regression line’s upward slope indicates that higher GDP per capita is associated with higher Scores, suggesting that greater economic output per person tends to correspond with higher well-being or happiness scores.

  • Spread of Residuals: Residual lengths vary, showing that the regression model does not perfectly predict the Scores. Some points are close to the regression line (small residuals), while others are further away (large residuals).

  • Heteroscedasticity: Residual spread increases with GDP per capita, suggesting potential heteroscedasticity. This indicates that the variability in Scores may be larger for countries with higher GDP per capita, affecting the reliability of the regression estimates.

  • Outliers: Some data points, especially at higher GDP per capita levels, are far from the regression line, indicating potential outliers that might significantly impact the regression model.

  1. Residuals vs Fitted plot

    • The points mostly fall along the reference line except for some deviations at both ends of the distribution, suggesting that most residuals are normally distributed but with potential outliers or heavy tails.

  • The confidence intervals for generosity and perceptions of corruption range from negative to positive values, indicating uncertainty about their effects on the score.

  • Narrow confidence intervals indicate more precise estimates, and intervals that exclude zero are usually considered statistically significant at the 95% confidence level, implying a non-zero effect of the variable on the score.


Significance test

Since the confidence interval for the Europe, Generosity and Perception of Corruption includes zero, suggesting that its effect on the score might not be statistically significant, we will carry out a t-test to reassess the significance of including these variables in our model.

t-test on Europe

Let \(\beta_2 = \text{Europe}\).

Determine at 5% significance level for testing \(β_2\) (Europe).

\(H_o:β_2=0 \quad vs \quad H_1:β_2\neq0\)

Decision rule: Reject \(H_o\) if \(\mid t_0 \mid > t_{\frac{\alpha}{2}, \enspace n-k-1}\)

From the summary, \(t_0 = 1.868\)

From the t-distribution table, \(t_{0.025, 149} = 1.9760\)

Decision: Since \(t_0 < 1.9760\) , we do not reject \(H_0\).

Conclusion: This indicates that \(\beta_2\) does not contribute significantly to the model given the other regressors is in the model at 5% level of significance.


t-test on Generosity

Let \(\beta_6 = \text{Generosity}\).

Determine at 5% significance level for testing \(β_6\) (Generosity).

\(H_o:β_6=0 \quad vs \quad H_1:β_6\neq0\)

Decision rule: Reject \(H_o\) if \(\mid t_0 \mid > t_{\frac{\alpha}{2}, \enspace n-k-1}\)

From the summary, \(t_0 = 1.006\)

From the t-distribution table, \(t_{0.025, 149} = 1.9760\)

Decision: Since \(t_0 < 1.9760\) , we do not reject \(H_0\).

Conclusion: This indicates that \(\beta_6\) does not contribute significantly to the model given the other regressors is in the model at 5% level of significance.


t-test on Perceptions of Corruptions

Let \(\beta_6 = \text{ Perceptions of Corruptions}\).

Determine at 5% significance level for testing \(β_7\) (Perceptions of Corruptions).

\(H_o:β_7=0 \quad vs \quad H_1:β_7\neq0\)

Decision rule: Reject \(H_o\) if \(\mid t_0 \mid > t_{\frac{\alpha}{2}, \enspace n-k-1}\)

From the summary, \(t_0 = 1.668\)

From the t-distribution table, \(t_{0.025, 149} = 1.9760\)

Decision: Since \(t_0 < 1.9760\) , we do not reject \(H_0\).

Conclusion: This indicates that \(\beta_7\) does not contribute significantly to the model given the other regressors is in the model at 5% level of significance.

Residuals Analysis

Summary
par(mfrow = c(2,2),mar =c(2,4,4,2), cex.lab = 0.8)
plot(full_model)

  1. Residual vs Fitted Values Plot

    • Ideally, residuals should be evenly scattered around the fitted line for a good fit. The slight convex curve in the plot suggests potential non-linearity in the relationship between predictors and response, indicating that the model may not be capturing some aspect of the data.

  1. Normal Q-Q Plot

    • This plot is used to check the assumption of normality of residuals. If the residuals are normally distributed, the points should fall approximately along the reference line. However, in the plot, the points seem to deviate from the line at both ends, suggesting potential departure from normality.

  1. Scale-Location Plot

    • This plot checks for a constant spread of residuals across fitted values, assessing the assumption of equal variance (homoscedasticity). The slight curve in this plot suggests potential non-linearity or heteroscedasticity (unequal variance of errors across different levels of the fitted values).

  1. Residuals vs Leverage Plot

    • This plot identifies influential cases by looking for points outside the dashed lines, indicating high Cook’s distance scores. Three influential cases are identified: #131, #148, and #152. These observations significantly affect the coefficients if deleted.

  • A forward selection technique was applied, which starts with no predictors and adds variables one at a time according to their correlation with the response variable, score.

  • The first variable added was GDP per capita, which has the highest correlation with the score. This reduced the AIC value to 325.93.

  • As other variables were added one by one, the AIC value increased, reaching a peak when the variable with the lowest correlation with the score, Generosity, was added. This suggests that variables with lower correlations result in higher AIC values.

  • A second model was selected, starting with a base model of Intercept and GDP per capita (the variable that resulted in the lowest AIC in the previous model) and adding other variables one by one according to their correlation with GDP per capita. The process was repeated until the lowest AIC was obtained.

  • The result of the forward selection was a model that excluded only Generosity from the full model, the same as the result from the stepwise regression method.

models <- list(full_model, MLR_2, MLR_3, MLR_4, MLR_5, stepwise_model, back_red_model)
models_names <- c("Model 1 (Full model)", "Model 2", "Model 3", "Model 4", 
                  "Model 5", "Model 6 (Stepwise model)", "Model 7 (Backward Reduction)")

results <- data.frame()

for(i in 1:length(models)) {
  summary_model <- summary(models[[i]])
  r_squared <- summary_model$r.squared
  adj_r_squared <- summary_model$adj.r.squared
  aic <- AIC(models[[i]])
  bic <- BIC(models[[i]])
  cp <- olsrr::ols_mallows_cp(models[[i]], full_model)
  num_params <- length(coefficients(models[[i]]))

  model_results <- data.frame(
    Model = paste(models_names[i]),
    p = num_params,
    R_Squared = r_squared,
    Adj_R_Squared = adj_r_squared,
    AIC = aic,
    BIC = bic,
    CP = cp
  )

  results <- rbind(results, model_results)
}

Based on the table above, Model 6 (Stepwise model) has been determined to be the best model. Here’s an explanation:

  1. R-Squared

    • Model 6 has the second-highest R-squared value (0.7827773), just slightly lower than Model 1 (Full model) but higher than all other models. Higher values are generally better as they indicate that more variance is explained by the model.

  1. Adjusted R-squared

    • Model 6 has the second-highest adjusted R-squared value (0.7740300), just slightly lower than Model 1 (Full model) but higher than all other models. This indicates that Model 6 explains a substantial proportion of the variance in the response variable while accounting for the number of predictors used.

  1. Akaike Information Criterion (AIC):

    • Model 6 has the lowest AIC value (252.9558) among all models, which suggests that it has the best goodness of fit while penalizing for the number of parameters. A lower AIC indicates a better model.

  1. Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC):

    • Model 6 has a relatively low BIC value (277.3547), which, while slightly higher than Model 3, 4 and 5, is still competitive. BIC also penalizes for the number of parameters but does so more harshly than AIC. A lower BIC generally indicates a better model.

  1. Mallows’ Cp:

    • A Cp value close to the number of parameters indicates a good fit. Model 6 has a Mallows’ Cp value (7.012228) close to the number of parameters (7), which suggests that it is relatively unbiased and has an appropriate number of predictors.

Summary:

Model 6 (Stepwise model) is chosen as the best model because it strikes a balance between model complexity and goodness of fit. It has:

  • The second-highest R-squared and Adjusted R-Squared value, indicating good explanatory power.

  • The lowest AIC, suggesting the best fit among the models while considering the number of predictors.

  • A competitive BIC value, indicating a good balance between model fit and complexity.

  • A Mallows’ Cp value close to p, indicating it is relatively unbiased with an appropriate number of predictors.

Interpretation for estimated coefficients:

  • Intercept, \(\beta_0\)​: On average, the model predicts the score will be 1.9548 when all other predictors (GDP, Europe, SS, HLE, FTMLC, and POC) are zero. This represents the baseline score.

  • Slope, \(\beta_1\)​ (GDP): Given that SS, HLE, FTMLC, and POC are held constant, the model predicts that the score will increase, on average, by 0.7104 for each one-unit increase in GDP per capita.

  • Slope, \(\beta_2\) (Europe): Given that GDP, SS, HLE, FTMLC, and POC are held constant, the model predicts that the score will increase, on average, by 0.2163 for each one-unit increase in the Europe variable.

  • Slope, \(β_3​\) (SS), \(β_4​\) (HLE), \(β_5\) (FTMLC​), and \(β6​\) (POC): Similary, the coefficients for these variables would interpret the average increase in the score for each unit increase in these variables, holding all other variables constant.

R-squared: 78.28% of the variation in \(Score\) can be explained by variation in \(GDP\), \(Europe\), \(SS\), \(HLE\), \(FTMLC\),and \(POC\).


Research Support

We have conducted a comprehensive study to examine and validate the relationship between the factors included in our best model and the response variable, Happiness Score. This analysis was undertaken to ensure the effectiveness of our chosen model in accurately predicting happiness scores based on these factors. Our findings provide robust support for the predictive capabilities of our model.

Why remove the “Generosity” variable?

Based on our analysis, the generosity factor is excluded from the best model. This is due to several reasons:

  1. Changes in happiness were driven by the commitment to be generous, rather than the amount spent. This suggests the act of committing to be generous impacts happiness more than the actual level of generosity.
  1. Brain regions involved in empathy and social cognition play a significant role in achieving happiness through generous behaviour. These regions must override selfish motives, implying that intention and commitment are more important than the actual act. (Park, S. et al., 2017).
  1. The study also confirms previous findings by Dunn et al., who reported that the amount of money spent on others is indirectly related to happiness, strengthening our analysis that the generosity variable is not a significant predictor of happiness. 


Correlation of Economic Growth (GDP) and Happiness (Score)

  • We then continue to discuss the correlation of the factors which should be included into the best model. First, multiple studies have demonstrated a significant correlation between economic growth and happiness. Data from the World Values Survey reveal that as income increases, happiness also rises within and across the countries over time (Ortiz-Ospina & Roser, 2024). An increase in income improves economic stability, allowing individuals to meet their basic needs such as food, shelter, and healthcare and reduce economic burdens, thus individuals tend to be happier. GDP per capita is a key indicator that measures the average economic output per person and reflects the overall economic well-being of a country. Higher GDP per capita often corresponds to better living standards, greater economic stability, and lower unemployment rates, which positively impact happiness (Helliwell, J.F. et al.,2020). This is supported by another study, as GDP per capita increases, there is a positive, statistically significant correlation with a slight increase in happiness (Stevenson, 2021). Additionally, based on our data for happiness index, the higher-ranked countries have considerably consistently high GDP per Capita with little variation within these countries. 


Correlation of Region or Country (Europe) and Happiness (Score)

  • Moreover, the correlation between region or country and happiness is multifaced. Recent data show that European countries consistently achieve high happiness scores, with Finland, Denmark, Iceland, Switzerland, and the Netherlands at the top. In contrast, outside of Europe, there are significant variations; countries in central Sub-Saharan Africa, such as Afghanistan and South Sudan, tend to have lower happiness scores (Ortiz-Ospina & Roser, 2024).


Correlation of Social Support (SS) and Happiness (Score)

  • Aristotle was the first to acknowledge humans as social animals. This means humans live and conduct activities in social relationships such as families and friends. Several studies have proven that having supportive relationships contributes to our psychological well-being. These relationships prevent loneliness by providing a sense of belonging. Besides, they also boost our feeling of self-worth and our belief that we are valuable. A supportive social network also ensures security and offers advice, guidance, and motivation when required. A Harvard study called Very Happy People found that there was a 0.7 correlation between social support and happiness (Social Connections and Happiness, n.d.). Thus, the correlation between social support and happiness is clear. Strong social connections fulfil fundamental emotional and psychological needs which contribute to higher levels of happiness, lower levels of stress, and better mental health outcomes.  


Correlation of Health life expectancy (HLE) and Happiness (Score)

  • Healthy life expectancy, defined as the average number of years a person is expected to live in good health, has also proven strongly correlated with happiness. The World Health Organization’s (WHO) data analyzed in World Happiness Report 2020, which includes data from 2019, shows that countries with higher healthy life expectancy reported higher levels of happiness. (Helliwell et al., 2020). A group of researchers’ study from Singapore also supports this connection. They found that happier people generally have lower mortality rates. They tend to live longer even after adjusting for various sociodemographic, physical, and psychological health factors. Happiness is also linked to lower rates of chronic diseases, which in turn extends life expectancy. (Song, C.F. et al., 2023). In summary, both sources highlight the positive influence of happiness on longevity, suggesting the high relationship between healthy life expectancy and happiness.


Correlation of Freedom to make life choices (FTMLC) and Happiness (Score)

  • An article from City Journal discusses how perceived freedom is strongly correlated with happiness. According to the General Social Survey, individuals who feel completely or very free are more likely to describe themselves as very happy compared to those who feel moderately or less free. This correlation remains even after controlling for variables such as income, education, and family status (Brooks, 2008). Moreover, the article also mentioned a 2003 study of German senior citizens in which the researcher found that a low level of perceived personal freedom strongly predicted depression. The findings suggest that freedom to make life choices has an impact on happiness, emphasizing its importance in enhancing life satisfaction.


Correlation of Perceptions of corruption (POC) and Happiness (Score)

  • A cross-national study of 126 countries revealed that a 10-point increase in corruption resulted in a 0.23-point decline in the national average of subjective well-being (Li, Q., & An, L., 2020). Thus, the research highlights a strong connection between perceptions of corruption and happiness, suggesting that people’s life satisfaction and overall happiness decline as they perceive more corruption. When additional factors are taken into consideration, this relationship remains robust. This reveals that corruption has an adverse impact on subjective well-being. As the corruption level rises, trust among citizens declines, leading to reduced happiness levels.

Studentized residuals
# Studentized residuals
stu_res_stepwise <- studres(stepwise_model)
dfstures_stepwise <- data.frame(stu_res_stepwise)
dfstures_stepwise$x <- seq(1:nrow(data_2019))


Histogram for standardized & studentized residuals
sta_hist2 <- ggplot(dfstares_stepwise, aes(x = sta_res_stepwise)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, fill = "coral4")


stu_hist2 <- ggplot(dfstures_stepwise, aes(x = stu_res_stepwise)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, fill = "darkslateblue")

ggarrange(sta_hist2, stu_hist2, ncol = 2, nrow = 1)

  1. Shape and Center:

    • Both histograms are bell-shaped and peak at zero, indicating that most residuals are centered around zero. This suggests a generally good fit of the model to the data.

  1. Skewness:

    • Both histograms exhibit a slight left skew, implying that there are more negative residuals than positive ones. This skewness points to the presence of negative outliers that might be affecting the model.

  1. Spread:

    • Both the standardized and studentized residuals range from approximately -4 to +2, with the majority of residuals falling between -2 and +2. This indicates similar variability in the residuals around the fitted values.

  1. Normality Assumption:

    • The bell-shaped distribution in both histograms supports the normality assumption of residuals, which is crucial for the validity of linear regression models.


Scatterplots of standardized & studentized residuals
#standardized residuals
sta_plot2 <- ggplot() + geom_point(data = dfstares_stepwise, aes(x = x, y = sta_res_stepwise), color = "cornflowerblue")

# Studentized residuals
stu_plot2 <- ggplot() + geom_point(data = dfstures_stepwise, aes(x = x, y = stu_res_stepwise), color = "brown3")

ggarrange(sta_plot2, stu_plot2, ncol = 2, nrow = 1)

  1. Pattern in Residuals

    • There is a noticeable pattern where residuals are higher for lower values of \(x\) and decrease as \(x\) increases, indicating potential non-linearity that the linear model is not capturing well.

  1. Heteroscedasticity

    • The residuals’ spread changes with \(x\), being more tightly clustered in the middle range (50 to 100) and more spread out at the edges. This suggests heteroscedasticity, violating the linear regression assumption of constant variance, which could impact regression estimates’ efficiency and hypothesis tests’ validity.

  1. Outliers

    • Observations greater than 2 or less than -2 are considered potential outliers. There are a few points, especially around \(x = 150\), where residuals are far from zero, indicating potential outliers that might disproportionately affect the regression model.

  1. Residual Centering

    • The residuals generally center around zero, indicating no consistent bias in the model’s predictions. This is a good sign, showing that the model does not systematically over- or under-predict the response variable.

As studentized residuals are adjusted for the influence of each data point, the observations on the scatterplot of the studentized residuals are more sensitive. 


Conclusion

Our comprehensive regression analysis on the 2019 happiness score data from Kaggle has yielded significant insights into the factors influencing global happiness scores. By analyzing factors such as GDP per capita, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make life choices, generosity, perceptions of corruption, and the categorical variable Region_europe (European vs. non-European), we have successfully identified the optimal combination of variables that best predict happiness scores and developed a robust model for determining happiness.

Key findings include:

  1. Simple Linear Regression:

    • Most Influential Variable: GDP per capita emerged as the most influential factor, exhibiting the highest correlation with happiness scores.

    • Model Development: A simple linear regression model was developed between GDP per capita and happiness scores.

    • Validation: This model was validated through various regression analyses, including scatterplots, prediction modeling, ANOVA tables, and residual analysis. The results confirmed the robustness and validity of the model, reinforcing the significant role of GDP per capita in predicting happiness scores.

  1. Multiple Linear Regression Model:

    • Comprehensive Analysis: A multiple linear regression model incorporating all relevant variables was created.

    • Validation: This comprehensive model underwent rigorous validation through regression analyses.

  1. Variable & Model Selection:

    • Selection Techniques: Several model selection techniques were employed to identify and refine the best-fit model., including:

      • Adjusted R-squared

      • Akaike Information Criterion (AIC)

      • Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)

      • Stepwise, Backward Stepwise, and Forward Stepwise Regression

      • Backward Reduction method using the F-test

  1. Best-fit Model (Model 6):

    • Stepwise Selection Method: Model 6, derived using the stepwise selection method, was identified as the optimal model.

    • Balance of Complexity and Fit: This model optimally balances model complexity and goodness of fit, making it the most effective model for predicting happiness scores.

    • Variable Inclusion: Notably, Model 6 excludes the variable ‘generosity’ but includes all other significant variables, highlighting the relative importance of these factors in influencing happiness scores.

    • Robustness and Accuracy: A series of regression analyses were conducted on this multiple linear regression model to ensure its robustness and accuracy.


Recommendations

We have made some recommendations on improving happiness based on our best model. These include:

  1. Enhance GDP per capita

    • Governments play a pivotal role in enhancing the quality of life and creating environments that support the well-being and happiness of citizens. Our analysis found that GDP per capita is the most significant variable influencing the Happiness Score, with a correlation of 0.79. Therefore, governments could focus on policies that promote economic growth and increase GDP per capita. This could include investing in education, infrastructure, and technology to boost productivity and economic well-being. In terms of policy implications, policymakers should prioritize happiness alongside economic growth as a core principle of government policy. Evidence supports the approach of countries like Scotland, New Zealand, and Iceland, which emphasize citizen well-being within their national development strategies. Policymakers should aim to enhance happiness through initiatives that improve the quality of life, offer robust social support, promote work-life balance, and invest in education and healthcare (Lee & Goh, 2023).

  1. Strengthen Social support 

    • To increase happiness, we should prioritize strengthening social support. Based on our analysis, social support is one of the most important factors influencing happiness scores in the best model. According to HelpGuide.org (2024), good relationships improve overall happiness. To strengthen social support, it is essential to focus on building and nurturing robust social networks within communities. Encouraging activities that foster community connections, such as social events, support groups, and collective projects, can enhance social support. Joining clubs related to our interests, participating in team sports, and engaging in volunteer work are other effective ways to connect with others. Being part of a group provides a sense of belonging and support, which is beneficial to mental health (Cherry, 2023). Regular interaction with others helps individuals experience less loneliness and isolation, lowering the likelihood of depression and anxiety. Additionally, volunteering provides a sense of meaning and accomplishment, further enhancing life satisfaction and contributing to community growth (Robinson, 2024).

By focusing on these key areas, policymakers can create an environment that supports the well-being and happiness of citizens.
